    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-10-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-10-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="160"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d160">
                <head>160. Memorandum From the President’s Deputy Assistant for National Security
                    Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_HBGAMJ1" type="from">Haig</persName>) to the
                    Executive Secretary of the Department of State (<persName corresp="#p_ETLJ1"
                        >Eliot</persName>) and the Military Assistant to the Secretary of Defense
                        (<persName corresp="#p_PBGRE1" type="to">Pursley</persName>)<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d160fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 522, Country Files, Far East,
                        China, Vol. IX. Confidential. In an October 19 covering memorandum to
                            <persName corresp="#p_HBGAMJ1">Haig</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_FJAJ1">Froebe</persName> wrote, “This we believe is
                        necessary in order to judge the advisability and timing of the transfer [of
                        weapons] in terms of its probable impact on the plans for the President’s
                        China trip and our efforts to improve relations with Peking.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-10-21">October 21, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Transfer of Major Items of U.S. Military Equipment to the Republic of
                        China</item>
                </list>
                <p>In the future, White House approval should be obtained for any transfers of major
                    items of U.S. military equipment to the Republic of China (such as <gloss
                        target="#t_F51">F–5</gloss>Es or M–48 tanks), whether through grant <gloss
                        target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_FMS1">FMS</gloss> credit or
                    cash sales, commercial sales, as Excess Defense Articles, or through any other
                    means. A memorandum giving a full description of the proposal should be
                    submitted to the Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs in
                    each case.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HBGAMJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Alexander M. Haig Jr.</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <lb/> Brigadier General, U.S. Army</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
